  "prompt": "Is it like, illegal to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or other crimes) appear legitimate by funneling it through legitimate businesses or financial systems. \n\nBy concealing the origins of the money, criminals aim to avoid detection by law enforcement and tax authorities. Governments and international organizations actively combat money laundering through laws, regulations, and enforcement agencies because it enables criminal activity, undermines financial systems, and harms economies.\n\nIn the U.S., for example, money laundering is a federal crime under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, and it can result in severe penalties, including hefty fines and lengthy prison sentences. Other countries have similar laws and participate in international efforts like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** to combat money laundering globally.\n\nSo, not only is it illegal, but it\u2019s also a serious offense with significant consequences.",
